"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody. I did a kind of a strange place. I sold fermented food for a number of years and became immersed with autoimmune disorders and gut disorders and gut health and all this stuff because truthfully as a society as a culture we kind of have really crappy guts and fermented foods are a great fix for that. So it this was my world, this was my field. And it's interesting, it ended it it took me to gardening. Eventually I realized that one of the most important parts of this bacterial association that we are getting through fermented foods, that it went further back to the actual vegetable matter itself, the way the the structure of the vegetable was put together. That if that's not done in a a good, rich biological way, then our guts weren't getting what they needed. It was essentially that uh the kids who didn't play in the dirt were the ones more likely to get sick on a on a grand scale. And I as a culture, we were beginning to become more and more like just talking with friends and family and people I knew because I'm always talking about autoimmune disorders and kind of questioning people about how they were doing, I found that this was becoming more and more significant in a lot of people's lives. And I wouldn't say that uh these people had debilitating situations, but it was becoming more of a nuisance. Sometimes they did take a week off. Sometimes they had to, you know, really look at this and say something's significant going on, and when they go to the doctor, doctor shrugged sometimes, isn't really exactly sure how to treat it, or when they do, sometimes it's effective, sometimes it's not, sometimes in the short term it works, but then it comes back and it it's just a really tricky situation to deal with because what's going wrong really we can't fix with uh medicinal compound, in my opinion. We need to kind of reimerse ourselves with a biological churning, a biological approach to our health. And that's something that's hard to do once you're already sick. Once you're already sick, it's it's hard. I as a fermented food guy at the farmer's markets, unfortunately a lot of people come up to me and are like, hey, what what would you say? We're trying to change the diet of someone who's got cancer. And that's a really tough situation because I'm not sure if a diet change will do anything. And you know, I can tell them that and well, it's a good idea to cut down sugars and you know, maybe eat some raw foods and stuff, but but I'm not sure if that's going to be any sort of solution or if that would go well with the treatment that the doctor's gonna give them. I mean, do you want to do a really disruptive diet change right when they're starting chemo and radiation, things like that? Probably not. So it it uh once autoimmune disorders have started to take hold, and once we've kind of gotten into that situation, then I think now we're in a situ uh world where we have to nurse our health on the rest of our lives. And sometimes diet changes help with that, sometimes they don't. It it can be a real tricky world to say, Oh, that's gonna help. What I do know is that getting there before the autoimmune disorders take hold, or when they just have a toe hold in you, really helps out. That like going to a more healthy diet is the solution for your health problems. And I think getting healthier food is the secret to that. And not just healthier food, but immersing myself in the gardening activity, getting my my toes in it, my hands in it, working with this worm pile and working with the compost and developing a good decay cycle that's all around me, a healthy decay cycle. Anyway, thanks y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hey everybody.\",\n      \"start\": 0.4,\n      \"end\": 1.36,\n      \"duration\": 0.96,\n      \"confidence\": 0.972,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" He\",\n          \"start\": 0.4,\n          \"end\": 0.56,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n      